            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/lots"]""",
            Tags = """["lots","traceability","quality","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"pl1","text":"What is the primary purpose of production lot tracking in QB Engineer?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"To count how many parts are in inventory at any given time"},{"id":"b","text":"To trace batches of parts back to their origin for recall capability, quality investigations, and regulatory compliance","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"To schedule production runs on the shop floor"},{"id":"d","text":"To calculate the cost of goods sold for each part"}],"explanation":"Lot tracking provides full traceability from raw material receipt through production, inspection, and shipment. This is essential for recalls, FDA/medical compliance, supplier accountability, and quality investigations."},{"id":"pl2","text":"A lot record must always be linked to which of the following?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A job and a production run"},{"id":"b","text":"A purchase order line and a supplier lot number"},{"id":"c","text":"A part — every lot must reference exactly one part","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"A QC inspection and a bin location"}],"explanation":"Part ID is the only required relationship. Every lot must be tied to exactly one part. Job, production run, purchase order line, and supplier lot number are all optional and depend on how the lot was created."},{"id":"pl3","text":"What format does QB Engineer use for auto-generated lot numbers?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"BATCH-{partNumber}-{sequence}"},{"id":"b","text":"LOT-YYYYMMDD-NNN (e.g., LOT-20260415-001)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"LR-{year}-{globalSequence}"},{"id":"d","text":"{partNumber}-{date}-{random}"}],"explanation":"Auto-generated lot numbers follow LOT-YYYYMMDD-NNN: a fixed 'LOT-' prefix, the UTC creation date, and a zero-padded daily sequence number. Custom lot numbers can be provided to override this format."},{"id":"pl4","text":"You receive raw material from a vendor. Which fields should you populate on the lot record?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Part ID, quantity, purchase order line ID, and supplier lot number","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Part ID, quantity, job ID, and production run ID"},{"id":"c","text":"Part ID, quantity, and expiration date only"},{"id":"d","text":"Only lot number and quantity — the system fills in the rest"}],"explanation":"For vendor-received material, link the lot to the PO line (purchase order line ID) and record the supplier's own batch identifier (supplier lot number). Job and production run are for internally produced lots."},{"id":"pl5","text":"A customer reports a defect in parts they received. What is the first step in the recall workflow?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Shut down all production lines immediately"},{"id":"b","text":"Identify the lot number from the part's label, shipping record, or customer complaint, then run a traceability query","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Contact the vendor and request a replacement shipment"},{"id":"d","text":"Delete the lot record to prevent further shipments"}],"explanation":"The first step is identifying the lot number and running a traceability query. This reveals the full chain: which jobs produced it, where remaining stock is stored, which QC inspections were performed, and which supplier material was used."},{"id":"pl6","text":"How does the lot detail panel present a lot's traceability?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only the lot record fields and the associated part number"},{"id":"b","text":"A part header (part number, quantity, supplier lot, expiration) plus a single chronological Trace History timeline that merges jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and QC inspections into one event stream","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Five separate tables — one each for jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and inspections"},{"id":"d","text":"The financial cost breakdown of producing this lot"}],"explanation":"The detail panel shows a header (part number, quantity, supplier lot, expiration) and a Trace History timeline. Related records — jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and QC inspections — are interleaved into one date-ordered event stream, each event with a type icon, reference number, description, and date. They are not displayed as five separate lists."},{"id":"pl7","text":"When should you set an expiration date on a lot record?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Always — every lot must have an expiration date for compliance"},{"id":"b","text":"When the material has a shelf life, such as adhesives, chemicals, or rubber compounds","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only for lots received from vendors, never for internally produced lots"},{"id":"d","text":"Only when the customer specifically requests lot expiration tracking"}],"explanation":"Expiration dates are for materials with a shelf life — adhesives, chemicals, perishable components. The field is optional and should be null for non-perishable materials like metal stock or hardware."},{"id":"pl8","text":"Which roles have access to the lot management API endpoints?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Admin and Manager only"},{"id":"b","text":"Admin, Manager, Engineer, and Production Worker","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Admin, Manager, and Engineer — Production Workers have read-only access"},{"id":"d","text":"All roles including Office Manager and PM"}],"explanation":"The LotsController is authorized for Admin, Manager, Engineer, and Production Worker roles. All four roles can create lots and run traceability queries."},{"id":"pl9","text":"How are lot records deleted in QB Engineer?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Hard deleted — the database row is permanently removed"},{"id":"b","text":"Soft deleted using a DeletedAt timestamp — the record is preserved but excluded from queries","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Archived to a separate history table"},{"id":"d","text":"Lot records cannot be deleted under any circumstances"}],"explanation":"Like all entities extending BaseEntity, lot records use soft delete via the DeletedAt timestamp. The global query filter automatically excludes deleted lots from all queries, but the data is preserved for audit trail and compliance."},{"id":"pl10","text":"You want to find all lots for a specific part that were received from vendors. How do you query the API?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"GET /api/v1/lots?partId={id} — then filter results client-side for those with a purchaseOrderLineId","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"GET /api/v1/lots/{partId}/vendor-lots"},{"id":"c","text":"GET /api/v1/parts/{id}/lots?source=vendor"},{"id":"d","text":"GET /api/v1/lots/trace?partId={id}&type=received"}],"explanation":"The GET /api/v1/lots endpoint accepts a partId query parameter to filter by part. The response includes purchaseOrderLineId and supplierLotNumber fields — lots with non-null values for these were received from vendors. There is no dedicated vendor-lot endpoint."}]}"""
        });

        // ── Create a Lot & Read Its Traceability (Walkthrough) ───────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Create a Lot and Read Its Traceability",
            Slug = "production-lots-create-trace-walkthrough",
            Summary = "An on-screen tour of the Lots list: search, open the New Lot dialog, and click a row to read its trace timeline.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Walkthrough,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/lots"]""",
            Tags = """["lots","traceability","quality","walkthrough"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"appRoute":"/lots","startButtonLabel":"Tour Production Lots","steps":[{"element":"app-page-header","popover":{"title":"The Lots List","description":"This is the Production Lots screen at /lots. Every lot you have recorded appears in one table — its lot number, part number and description, quantity, linked job, supplier lot number, expiration date, and the date it was created. This single list is your entry point for both creating new lots and looking up the history of an existing one.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".page-header","popover":{"title":"Search Lots","description":"Use this search box to find a lot fast. It matches on the lot number, the supplier's lot number, and the part number, so you can paste a number off a label, a packing slip, or a certificate of analysis and land on the right record. Type your term and click Search (or press Enter) to filter the table.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"[data-testid='new-lot-btn']","popover":{"title":"Create a New Lot","description":"Lots are created here, manually — the system does not auto-generate them in the background. Click New Lot to open the create dialog. You pick the Part (required) and enter a Quantity (required); everything else — a Linked Job, the Supplier Lot #, an Expiration Date, and Notes — is optional. The lot number itself is generated for you when you save, so you never type it. If you receive material for a part that isn't catalogued yet, the Part field lets you create the part inline without leaving the dialog.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":".page-header","popover":{"title":"Quantity Is Decimal","description":"The Quantity field accepts fractional amounts — it steps in 0.0001 increments. That means you record material tracked by weight, volume, or length exactly as it arrives (for example 12.5 kg or 3.75 m), not just whole-unit counts. Enter the real measured quantity rather than rounding to an integer.","side":"bottom"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Open a Lot to Trace It","description":"Click any row in this table to open that lot's detail panel. The panel opens over the list and the URL updates to ?detail=lot:<id>, so the view you are looking at is shareable and survives a refresh. This is how you go from 'which lot is this?' to its full history.","side":"left"}},{"element":"app-data-table","popover":{"title":"Reading the Trace Timeline","description":"Inside the detail panel, a header shows the part number, the quantity (to 4 decimal places), and — when present — the supplier lot number and expiration date. Below it, Trace History is a single chronological timeline: jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and QC inspections are merged into one date-ordered stream, each with its own icon, a reference number, a description, and a date. Read it top to bottom to follow the chain from raw-material receipt through production, inspection, and storage. A History tab on the panel records changes to the lot record itself.","side":"left"}}]}"""
        });

        // ── Reading the Lot Trace Timeline (Article) ─────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Reading the Lot Trace Timeline",
            Slug = "production-lots-reading-trace-timeline",
            Summary = "How to interpret a lot's detail panel: the part header and the single merged Trace History timeline of jobs, runs, POs, bins, and inspections.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/lots"]""",
            Tags = """["lots","traceability","quality"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Reading the Lot Trace Timeline\n\nThe payoff of lot tracking is the **detail panel** you reach by clicking a lot in the list at `/lots`. It answers, in one place, 'what is this lot and what has happened to it?' This article walks through every part of that panel so you can read a lot's history confidently.\n\n### Opening the Panel\n\nFrom the Lots list, click any row. The lot's detail panel opens over the list and the URL gains a `?detail=lot:<id>` segment, so the exact view is shareable and survives a browser refresh. Close it with the X in the panel header or the Escape key. The panel's title is the lot number itself.\n\n### The Part Header\n\nAt the top of the panel is a compact header that identifies the lot:\n\n- **Part Number** — the part this lot belongs to.\n- **Quantity** — the lot quantity, shown to **up to 4 decimal places**. Because lots can track material by weight, volume, or length, you may see values like `12.5000` or `3.7500`, not just whole numbers.\n- **Supplier Lot #** — the vendor's own batch identifier. This row appears **only when a supplier lot number was recorded**, so its presence tells you at a glance that the lot came from a vendor receipt.\n- **Expires** — the expiration date in `MM/dd/yyyy` form. This row appears **only when an expiration date was set**, which flags the lot as shelf-life-sensitive material.\n\nIf the supplier-lot or expiration rows are absent, that field was simply left blank on the lot — it is not an error.\n\n### Trace History — One Merged Timeline\n\nBelow the header is **Trace History**. This is the heart of the panel, and the single most important thing to understand about it is that it is **one chronological timeline, not five separate lists**. Records of five different kinds are interleaved into a single date-ordered event stream:\n\n| Icon | Event type | What it means |\n|---|---|---|\n| work | **Job** | A production job that produced or consumed parts from this lot. |\n| precision_manufacturing | **Production Run** | A specific production run linked to the lot — finer-grained than the job. |\n| description | **Purchase Order** | The PO (and vendor) that supplied the raw material for this lot. |\n| inventory_2 | **Bin Location** | An inventory location currently holding units from this lot. |\n| fact_check | **QC Inspection** | A quality inspection performed against this lot number. |\n\nEach event row shows its **icon**, a **reference number** (the job number, PO number, run number, bin path, or inspection identifier), a short **description**, and a **date** in `MM/dd/yyyy` form. Because everything is merged and ordered by date, you read the panel top-to-bottom to follow the real-world chain: raw-material receipt (PurchaseOrder) → production (Job / ProductionRun) → inspection (QcInspection) → storage (BinLocation). You do not have to cross-reference five tabs to assemble that story — the timeline already has.\n\nIf a lot has no related records yet, Trace History shows a short empty message instead of events. That is normal for a lot you just created and have not yet consumed, inspected, or stored.\n\n### The History Tab (Record Changes)\n\n Beneath the trace timeline, the panel also surfaces a **History** view scoped to this lot. Where Trace History shows *operational* events that touched the lot's material, the History view shows *edits to the lot record itself* — the audit trail of who changed what on the lot. Keep the two straight: Trace History answers 'where did this material go and come from?', History answers 'who changed this record?'.\n\n### Using the Panel in Practice\n\n**A customer reports a defect.** Read the lot number off the part or shipping record, search for it in the list, and open the panel. The PurchaseOrder event tells you which vendor batch supplied the raw material; the QcInspection events tell you whether inspection caught anything; the BinLocation events tell you whether any of this lot is still on the shelf to quarantine.\n\n**A periodic traceability audit.** Open a sample of lots and confirm each one shows the chain you expect — a received raw lot should have a PurchaseOrder event and a supplier lot number; a produced lot should have a Job (and ideally a ProductionRun) and at least one QcInspection. Gaps you find here are gaps you want to fix *before* a recall, not during one.\n\n**Confirming shelf life.** The Expires row in the header is the fastest check on whether material is still usable. No Expires row means no expiration was recorded — for shelf-life-sensitive material, that itself is a finding.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- The detail panel = **part header** + **one merged Trace History timeline** + a **History** record-change view.\n- Quantity renders to 4 decimals; supplier-lot and expiration rows appear only when those values exist.\n- Trace History interleaves Jobs, Production Runs, Purchase Orders, Bin Locations, and QC Inspections into a single date-ordered stream — read it top-to-bottom to follow the material's full chain.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Production Lots training modules");
    }
